  "chunk_index": 37,
  "summary": "Poirot corrects Edward Carter’s reasoning regarding the descriptions of a couple provided by witnesses Walter Stukey and Rafael Burbank. Poirot explains that the witnesses were not describing a single couple, but rather two different pairs consisting of an older wife and a younger husband. Poirot promises to take Carter to visit an acquaintance the following morning.\n\nThe next day, Poirot, Carter, and Pollock arrive at 3 Jermyn Street. Instead of the expected eyewitness Samuel Kid, they encounter a terrified Jane Hobbs. Pollock clarifies a misunderstanding from Carter's previous conversation with Stukey; Carter had believed Stukey said a woman \"wouldn't like a child,\" but Stukey had actually said she \"wouldn't like Semmy Kid\" (Samuel Kid). This revelation establishes that Jane Hobbs was previously engaged to Samuel Kid. Poirot further suggests that Jane’s past sadness may have stemmed from the death of her true love, Patrick Ivor, and that she had adopted a more noble manner of speaking to appear as his social equal.\n\nDuring the visit, Jane Hobbs claims that Nancy Duane killed Harriet, Ada, and Richard at the Blaxland Hotel. She asserts that Samuel Kid witnessed Nancy Duane fleeing the hotel and dropping two keys. Poirot rejects this accusation, calling Jane a liar and noting that the coincidence of her story is too convenient to be true.",
